â
âThis is it; he could turn aside the ordinary bullets, but he had no power over the youngsterâs, which was marked with a cross; it hit him in the shoulder, I saw him make a movement as if to try and bite himself.
â
âBut,â I broke in, astonished at the silence and amazement which had fallen on the keepers, âif my bullet hit him in the shoulder, why did it not kill him?
â
âBecause it was made neither of gold nor of silver, my dear boy; and because no bullets but those that are made of gold or silver can pierce the skin of the devil, or kill those who have made a compact with him.
â
âBut, Mocquet,â said the keepers, shuddering, âdo you really think ...?â
âThink?
Yes, I do!
